com.codename1.rad.nodes

Class FieldNode

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute<T>
      • com.codename1.rad.nodes.Node
        • com.codename1.rad.nodes.FieldNode
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Proxyable

    public class FieldNode
extends Node
implements Proxyable

    A Node that represents a field (usually editable) on a form. It can be added to a FormNode, or SectionNode, and can be bound to a Property using either Tags or PropertyNode attributes.

    Supported Attributes

    As with any node, there isn’t a fixed limit on the attributes that it can support, but common attributes that it accepts (and will be respected by the EntityEditor view, include:

    1. PropertyNode - A property that this field is bound to. Note that using a PropertyNode attribute produces strong coupling to the Property. It is almost always better to use Tags instead to bind the field to a list of tags, and allow dynamic field binding.

    2. Tags - A list of tags that this field will try to bind to dynamically. When the EntityEditor is created, it will try lookup the property of the Entity that contains one of these tags, and bind to that property.

    3. Property.Label - The widget label when rendered in the EntityEditor

    4. Property.Description - The widget description or help text when rendered in the EntityEditor.

    5. WidgetType - The widget type to use for editing this property. This is used by the PropertyViewFactory when creating the component.

    6. OptionsNode - For widgets that have "options" to choose from, such as comboboxes, this allows you to specify the options that are available to select.

    7. Property.Editable - Whether this widget is editable. (Though this attribute is often added to a parent node so that it is applied to all nodes in the branch.).

    Creating Fields

    UI contains convenience methods for creating FieldNode nodes of specific types. These are just thin wrappers around #FieldNode(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​) with WidgetType attributes set.

    1. com.codename1.rad.ui.UI#textArea(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​) - A multiline text area.

    2. com.codename1.rad.ui.UI#textField(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​) - Single-line text field.

    3. com.codename1.rad.ui.UI#comboBox(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​) - A combobox.

    4. com.codename1.rad.ui.UI#table(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​) - A table

    Note
    		 The EntityEditor class is still undergoing active development to add support for more widget types, improve styles, and add more features.

    Example

    The following is an example of a UI descriptor for editing a "Person" entity.

    A UI descriptor for a form to edit a "Person" entity
    package com.codename1.demos.ddddemo;

import com.codename1.rad.ui.UI;
import com.codename1.rad.nodes.ActionNode;
import static com.codename1.demos.ddddemo.PersonEntityType.*;
import com.codename1.ui.FontImage;
import static com.codename1.ui.FontImage.MATERIAL_DELETE;
import static com.codename1.rad.nodes.FormNode.OVERFLOW_MENU;
import static com.codename1.rad.nodes.FormNode.BOTTOM_RIGHT_MENU;
import static com.codename1.rad.nodes.FormNode.TOP_LEFT_MENU;


public class PersonEditor extends UI {

   // Define some actions
   public static ActionNode
       deleteAction = action(
           label("Delete"),
           description("Delete this user"),
           icon(MATERIAL_DELETE)
       ),
       showContactsAction = action(
           label("Open Contacts"),
           description("Show all contacts"),
           icon(FontImage.MATERIAL_CONTACTS)
       ),
       printAction = action(
           label("Print"),
           description("Print this page"),
           icon(FontImage.MATERIAL_PRINT)
       );

   {


       // Define the root form.
       form(
           actions(OVERFLOW_MENU, deleteAction, printAction),  (1)
           actions(TOP_LEFT_MENU, deleteAction, printAction, showContactsAction), (2)
           actions(BOTTOM_RIGHT_MENU, deleteAction, printAction), (3)
           editable(true),
           description("Please edit the person's information in the fields below"),
           label("Person Details"),
           columns(2),
           textField(
               label("Name"),
               description("Please enter your name"),
               tags(Person.name)
           ),
           textField(
               tags(description)
           ),
           comboBox(
               tags(DemoTags.hairColor)
           ),
           section(
               actions(TOP_LEFT_MENU, deleteAction, printAction),
               columns(1),
               label("Section 2"),
               textArea(
                   tags(DemoTags.userProfile)
               ),
               table(actions(OVERFLOW_MENU, deleteAction, printAction),
                  label("Quick Links"),
                  description("Useful links related to this person"),
                  editable(true),
                  //property(quicklinks),
                  tags(com.codename1.rad.schemas.Person.url),
                  columns(new QuickLinkEditor().getAllFields())
               )
           )

       );

}}

    1. We add an overflow menu to the form.

    2. Add some actions to the top-left menu.

    3. Add some actions to the bottom-right menu.

    Notice how succinct, yet readable this code is. We can convert this into an actual view with the following:

    new EntityEditor(entity, new PersonEditor());

    And the result:

    Figure 1. The UI generated from the above UI descriptor. All fields are bound to the entity, so changes to the entity will instantly update the UI, and vice-versa.

      • getPropertySelector

        public PropertySelector getPropertySelector(Entity context)

        Gets a property selector for this field node. If the filed contained a PropertyNode or a Tags node, then it will construct a selector from those.

        Otherwise it will check for a ProeprtySelectorAttribute, and return a selector constructed form that, with the provided entity root.

        Parameters:
        context -
        Returns:
        A property selector, or null if no property or tag is set, and no property selector is set.
